ian Albums Chart]]<ref>{{cite web| url=http://australian-charts.com/search.asp?search=stone+sour&cat=a| title=Simple Search: Stone Sour| publisher=Australian-Charts.com| accessdate=July 6, 2009}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|21\n|-\n|[[\u00d63 Austria Top 40|Austria Albums Chart]]<ref>{{cite web| url=http://austriancharts.at/search.asp?search=stone+sour&cat=a| title=Suche nach: Stone Sour| publisher=AustrianCharts.at| accessdate=July 6, 2009}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|13\n|-\n||[[Ultratop|Belgian Albums Chart]] ([[Flanders]])<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.ultratop.be/nl/search.asp?search=Stone+Sour&cat=a| title=Eenvoudige zoekopdracht:: Stone Sour| publisher=UltraTop.be| accessdate=July 6, 2009}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|34\n|-\n||Belgian Albums Chart ([[Wallonia]])<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.ultratop.be/fr/search.asp?search=Stone+Sour&cat=a| title=Eenvoudige zoekopdracht:: Stone Sour| publisher=UltraTop.be}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|82\n|-\n|[[Canadian Albums Chart]]<ref name=\"billboard\">{{cite magazine| url={{BillboardURLbyName|artist=stone sour|chart=all}} | title=Stone Sour Artist Chart History: Albums| magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]| accessdate=July 6, 2009}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|6\n|-\n|[[Finland's Official List|Finnish Albums Chart]]<ref>{{cite web| url=http://finnishcharts.com/search.asp?search=stone+sour&cat=a| title=Simple Search: Stone Sour| publisher=FinnishCharts.com| accessdate=July 6, 2009}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|21\n|-\n|[[Syndicat National de l'\u00c9dition Phonographique|French Albums Chart]]<ref>{{cite web| url=http://lescharts.com/search.asp?search=Stone+Sour&cat=a| title=Recherche normale: Stone Sour| publisher=LesCharts.com| accessdate=July 6, 2009}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|56\n|-\n|[[Media Control Charts|German Albums Chart]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.musicline.de/de/chartverfolgung_summary/artist/Stone+Sour/?type=longplay|title=Chartverfolgung / Stone Sour / Longplay|language=German|publisher=PhonoNet|access-date=2011-09-02|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6GcAomJ3d?url=http://www.musicline.de/de/chartverfolgung_summary/artist/Stone+Sour/?type=longplay|archive-date=2013-05-14|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|18\n|-\n|[[Irish Albums Chart]]<ref>{{cite web| url=http://irish-charts.com/showinterpret.asp?interpret=Stone+Sour| title=Simple Search: Stone Sour| publisher=Irish-charts.com}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|33\n|-\n|[[Oricon|Japanese Albums Chart]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oricon.co.jp/prof/artist/303356/ranking/cd_album/|title=\u30b9\u30c8\u30fc\u30f3\u30fb\u30b5\u30ef\u30fc\u306eCD\u30a2\u30eb\u30d0\u30e0\u30e9\u30f3\u30ad\u30f3\u30b0\u3001\u30b9\u30c8\u30fc\u30f3\u30fb\u30b5\u30ef\u30fc\u306e\u30d7\u30ed\u30d5\u30a3\u30fc\u30eb\u306a\u3089\u30aa\u30ea\u30b3\u30f3\u82b8\u80fd\u4eba\u4e8b\u5178 \u2013 Oricon Style |publisher=Oricon.co.jp |accessdate=April 26, 2013}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|44\n|-\n|[[MegaCharts|Netherlands Albums Chart]]<ref>{{cite web| url=http://dutchcharts.nl/search.asp?search=Stone+Sour&cat=a| title=Search for: Stone Sour| publisher=DutchCharts.nl| accessdate=July 6, 2009}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|33\n|-\n|[[Recording Industry Association of New Zealand|New Zealand Albums Chart]]<ref>{{cite web| url=https://charts.nz/search.asp?search=Stone+Sour&cat=a| title=Simple Search: Stone Sour| publisher=charts.nz| accessdate=July 6, 2009}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|31\n|-\n|[[Sverigetopplistan|Swedish Albums Chart]]<ref>{{cite web| url=http://swedishcharts.com/search.asp?search=Stone+Sour&cat=a| title=Simple search: Stone Sour| publisher=SwedishCharts.com| accessdate=July 6, 2009}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|30\n|-\n|[[Swiss Music Charts|Swiss Albums Chart]]<ref>{{cite web| url=http://hitparade.ch/search.asp?search=stone+sour&cat=a| title=Einfache Suche: Stone Sour| publisher=HitParade.ch| accessdate=July 6, 2009}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|25\n|-\n|[[UK Albums Chart]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/artist/_/stone%20sour/|title=Stone Sour UK Chart History|work=[[Official Charts Company]]|accessdate=July 30, 2013}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|27\n|-\n|US [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]]<ref name=\"billboard\"/>\n|align=\"center\"|4\n|-\n|US Digital Albums Chart<ref name=\"billboard\"/>\n|align=\"center\"|4\n|-\n|US Rock Albums Chart<ref name=\"billboard\"/>\n|align=\"center\"|1\n|-\n|US Tastemakers Albums Chart<ref name=\"billboard\"/>\n|align=\"center\"|3\n|}\n\n==Certifications==\n{{Certification Table Top}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=United States|artist=Stone Sour|title=Come What(Ever)|type=album|award= Platinum |relyear=2006|certyear= 2017|accessdate=July 21, 2017}}\n{{Certification Table Bottom|streaming=true}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{StoneSour}}\n\n{{good article}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Come What(Ever) May}}\n[[Category:2006 albums]]\n[[Category:Stone Sour albums]]\n[[Category:Roadrunner Records albums]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Nick Raskulinecz]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox album\n| italic_title = force\n| name         = Come What(ever) May\n| type         = studio\n| artist       = [[Stone Sour]]\n| cover        = Come What(ever) May.jpg\n| alt          =\n| released     = {{Start date|2006|8|01}}\n| recorded     = January \u2013 April 2006 at Studio 606 in [[Northridge, Los Angeles, California|Northridge]], [[Los Angeles]], [[California]]\n| venue        =\n| studio       =\n| genre        = {{flatlist|\n* [[Alternative metal]]\n* [[post-grunge]]\n* [[hard rock]]\n}}\n| length       = 48:54\n| label        = [[Roadrunner Records|Roadrunner]]\n| producer     = [[Nick Raskulinecz]]\n| prev_title   = [[Stone Sour (album)|Stone Sour]]\n| prev_year    = 2002\n| next_title   = [[Live in Moscow (album)|Live in Moscow]]\n| next_year    = 2007\n| misc         = {{Extra album cover\n | header  = Alternative cover\n | type    = studio\n | cover   = Stonesourspecialedition.gif\n | border  =\n | alt     =\n | caption = Special edition album cover\n}}\n {{Singles\n | name        = Come What(ever) May\n | type        = studio\n | single1     = [[30/30-150]]\n | single1date = June 3, 2006\n | single2     = [[Through Glass]]\n | single2date = July 22, 2006\n | single3     = [[Sillyworld]]\n | single3date = March 9, 2007\n | single4     = [[Made of Scars]]\n | single4date = June 11, 2007\n | single5     = [[Zzyzx Rd. (song)|Zzyzx Rd.]]\n | single5date = October 5, 2007\n}}\n}}\n'''''Come What(ever) May''''' is the second studio album by American [[Rock music|rock]] band [[Stone Sour]]. It was recorded and produced by the band and [[Nick Raskulinecz]] at Studio 606 in [[Los Angeles]], [[California]], and was released on August 1, 2006, by [[Roadrunner Records]]. Writing for the album began as early as 2003 when vocalist [[Corey Taylor]] and guitarist [[Jim Root|James Root]] were writing material for their other band, [[Slipknot (band)|Slipknot]]. In January 2006, Stone Sour began recording their second album, during which time drummer Joel Ekman left the band because of family constraints. He was eventually replaced by ex-[[Soulfly]] drummer [[Roy Mayorga]] who played on all but two tracks on the album.\n\nFollowing the release of the album, Stone Sour promoted it for over a year, releasing five singles and touring in the United States, Canada, Japan and several countries in Europe. The album received generally positive reviews. It was praised for showing a progression in the band's song writing ability and musical style. It was also certified Platinum in the United States and the single \"30/30-150\" was nominated for Best Metal Performance at the 49th Grammy Awards. On June 26, 2007, Stone Sour released a special edition version of the album; it included six previously unreleased tracks and a bonus DVD with three music videos and a complete live performance by the band in [[Moscow]]. It remains their best-selling album to date, mostly due to the success of the single \"[[Through Glass]]\". As proof of this, the album became their first to be certified Platinum by the [[Recording Industry Association of America|RIAA]] which occurred on July 21, 2017.<ref>{{cite web|title=Stone Sour's 'Come What(ever) May' Certified Platinum By RIAA|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/stone-sours-come-whatever-may-certified-platinum-by-riaa/|website=[[Blabbermouth]]|accessdate=2017-08-01}}</ref>\n\n== Production ==\nIn September 2005, lead singer Corey Taylor announced that Stone Sour would return with a second album.<ref name=\"BM1\">{{cite news |title = Stone Sour: Producer Announced; Recording To Begin In January |website = [[Blabbermouth.net]] |date = September 20, 2005 |url = http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/stone-sour-producer-announced-recording-to-begin-in-january/|accessdate = July 6, 2009 }}</ref> He said that they had written over 30&nbsp;songs, some during the writing process of ''[[Vol. 3: (The Subliminal Verses)]]'', the third album by vocalist Taylor and guitarist James Root's other band [[Slipknot (band)|Slipknot]], and that they were working on demoing the tracks before entering the studio.<ref name=\"BM1\"/><ref name=\"MTV1\"/> [[Dave Fortman]] was originally scheduled to produce the album, but on January 22, 2006 Stone Sour began working on the album with producer [[Nick Raskulinecz]] at [[Dave Grohl]]'s personal studio (Studio 606), in [[Los Angeles]].<ref name=\"BM1\"/><ref name=\"MTV1\">{{cite news |last = Harris |first = Chris |title = Slipknot's Taylor Gearing Up For Stone Sour LP \u2014 And Tenacious D Tribute |website = [[MTV]] |date = January 26, 2006 |url = http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1520740/20060113/stone_sour.jhtml |accessdate = July 6, 2009}}</ref> Time in the studio began with a week of pre-production, during which the guitarist [[Josh Rand]] said that Raskulinecz \"pushed [the band] to the brink and back\" to help fine-tune the songs they had previously written.<ref name=\"BM2\">{{cite news |title = Stone Sour: Ex-Soulfly Drummer Mayorga To Play On New Album |website = Blabbermouth.net |date = February 16, 2006 |url = http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/stone-sour-ex-soulfly-drummer-mayorga-to-play-on-new-album/ |accessdate = July 6, 2009 }}</ref> first album, writing for ''Come What(ever) May'' was by all members.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.rocknworld.com/morley/06/StoneSour.shtml|title= MorleyView: Stone Sour Interview|author= Morley Seaver|publisher= antiMusic.com|accessdate=December 26, 2009}}</ref>\n\nFollowing this, the band set out to record 18 tracks and work began on recording Joel Ekman's drum tracks. However, Ekman was forced to leave the studio after four weeks because of his young son's diagnosis of a [[brainstem glioma]].<ref name=\"BM2\"/> With the fate of the album in jeopardy, Stone Sour recruited Mayorga, ex-Soulfly, as a session drummer.<ref name=\"BM2\"/> Mayorga recorded drums for all but two tracks on the album, [[Godsmack]] drummer [[Shannon Larkin]] performed on the track \"[[30/30-150]]\" and guitarist Root performed drums on the bonus track \"The Day I Let Go\".<ref name=\"booklet\">{{cite AV media notes |title= Come What(ever) May|titlelink= Come What(ever) May|others= [[Stone Sour]]|year= 2006|publisher= [[Roadrunner Records]]|type=booklet}}</ref> In an interview with ''[[Revolver (magazine)|Revolver]]'' during the recording process, the vocalist Taylor talked about the differences between this album and their previous album, ''Stone Sour''.<ref name=\"BM3\">{{cite news |title = Slipknot Singer Says New Stone Sour Album Will Be 'Miles Above The First One' |website = Blabbermouth.net |date = March 23, 2006 |url = http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=50034 |accessdate = July 6, 2009 |url-status = dead |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070321064346/http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=50034 |archivedate = March 21, 2007 }}</ref> He said that pressures from fans and the record label were much larger, also noting that he \"thrives on the pressure, because it gets [him] going\". While promising, \"The album's gonna be miles above the first one,\" Taylor explained that it is \"more melodic and darker\".<ref name=\"BM3\"/> In late March 2006, drummer Joel Ekman officially left Stone Sour and the band was talking with a few drummers who could replace him.<ref name=\"BM4\">{{cite news |title = Stone Sour Part Ways With Drummer |website = Blabbermouth.net |date = March 24, 2006 |url = http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/stone-sour-part-ways-with-drummer/|accessdate = July 6, 2009 }}</ref> On April 7, 2006, the recording sessions for ''Come What(ever) May'' concluded.<ref>{{cite news |title = Stone Sour Finish Recording New Album |website = Blabbermouth.net |date = April 7, 2006 |url = http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/stone-sour-finish-recording-new-album/ |accessdate = July 6, 2009 }}</ref> A month later, Mayorga joined Stone Sour full-time .<ref>{{cite news |title = Stone Sour Comment On New Drummer Roy Mayorga |website = Blabbermouth.net |date = May 11, 2006 |url = http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/stone-sour-comment-on-new-drummer-roy-mayorga/ |accessdate = July 6, 2009 }}</ref>\n\n== Promotion ==\nIn March 2006, it was announce that \"Come What May,\" would be released on July 18, 2006.<ref name=\"BM4\"/> However, the release date for the album was pushed back until August 22.<ref name=\"BM5\"/> Because of the delay, Stone Sour released a music video for the track \"Reborn\", which had footage of the band working on the album in the studio.<ref name=\"BM5\">{{cite news |title = Stone Sour To Film 'Through Glass' Video |website = Blabbermouth.net |date = May 3, 2006 |url = http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/stone-sour-to-film-through-glass-video/ |accessdate = July 6, 2009 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title = Stone Sour: Video For New Song 'Reborn' Posted Online |website = Blabbermouth.net |date = April 28, 2006 |url = http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/stone-sour-video-for-new-song-reborn-posted-online/ |accessdate = July 6, 2009 }}</ref> The album's cover artwork was released online on May 20, 2006.<ref name=\"BM6\">{{cite news |title = Stone Sour: New Album Artwork Posted Online |website = Blabbermouth.net |date = May 20, 2006 |url = http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=52563 |archive-url = https://archive.today/20130201085445/http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=52563 |url-status = dead |archive-date = February 1, 2013 |accessdate = July 6, 2009 }}</ref> Shortly after, it was confirmed by a representative from the band's record label, [[Roadrunner Records|Roadrunner]], that the release date had been brought forward, and the official release date would be August 1, 2006.<ref>{{cite news |title = Stone Sour: New Album Release Date Officially Moved Forward |website = Blabbermouth.net |date = May 24, 2006 |url = http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=52765 |archive-url = https://archive.today/20120630105521/http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=52765 |url-status = dead |archive-date = June 30, 2012 |accessdate = July 6, 2009 }}</ref> On July 31, 2006, the day before its release the album was made available online for streaming in its entirety through [[AOL]].<ref>{{cite news |title = Stone Sour: Entire New Album Available For Streaming |website = Blabbermouth.net |date = July 31, 2006 |url = http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/stone-sour-entire-new-album-available-for-streaming/ |accessdate = July 6, 2009 }}</ref>\n\nOn May 22, 2006, the first single from the album, \"30/30-150\", was made available online as a free MP3 download.<ref name=\"BM6\"/> A music video for the single was shot with director [[P.R. Brown]] in Los Angeles and received a premier on [[MTV]]'s ''[[Headbangers Ball]]'' on June 3, 2006.<ref>{{cite news |title = Stone Sour: '30/30-150' Video To Receive 'Headbanger's Ball' Premiere This Weekend |website = Blabbermouth.net |date = June 1, 2006 |url = http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=53112 |accessdate = July 6, 2009 |url-status = dead |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20090820021744/http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=53112 |archivedate = August 20, 2009 }}</ref> Prior to the release of the second single from the album, \"[[Through Glass]]\", radio stations throughout the US showed high support for the song.<ref>{{cite news |title = Stone Sour Making 'Huge Impact' With New Single 'Through Glass' |website = Blabbermouth.net |date = June 6, 2006 |url = http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/stone-sour-making-huge-impact-with-new-single-through-glass/ |accessdate = July 6, 2009 }}</ref> A music video for the single was shot with director [[Tony Petrossian]] and was released online on June 9, 2006, through [[Yahoo!]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Stone Sour: 'Through Glass' Video Posted Online |website=Blabbermouth.net |date=July 9, 2006 |url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/stone-sour-through-glass-video-posted-online/ |accessdate=July 6, 2009}}</ref> The third single from the album, \"[[Sillyworld]]\", began receiving radio airplay in November 2006.<ref>{{cite news |title = Stone Sour Sending 'Sillyworld' To Radio |website = Blabbermouth.net |date = November 20, 2006 |url = http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/stone-sour-sending-sillyworld-to-radio/ |accessdate = July 6, 2009 }}</ref> A music video for the single was shot in January 2007 and was released online on March 8, 2007.<ref>{{cite news |title = Stone Sour To Film 'Sillyworld' Video Next Week |website = Blabbermouth.net |date = January 6, 2007 |url = http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/stone-sour-to-film-sillyworld-video-next-week/ |accessdate = July 6, 2009 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title = Stone Sour: 'Sillyworld' Video Posted Online |website = Blabbermouth.net |date = March 8, 2007 |url = http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=68411 |accessdate = July 6, 2009 |url-status = dead |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070313034936/http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=68411 |archivedate = March 13, 2007 }}</ref> The fourth single from the album, \"[[Made of Scars]]\", had a music video which was recorded live on April 7, 2007, and was posted online on June 5, 2007.<ref>{{cite news |title = Stone Sour Films 'Made Of Scars' Video In Philadelphia |website = Blabbermouth.net |date = April 18, 2007 |url = http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=70786 |accessdate = July 6, 2009 |url-status = dead |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070711165810/http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=70786 |archivedate = July 11, 2007 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title = Stone Sour: 'Made Of Scars' Video Posted Online |website = Blabbermouth.net |date = June 5, 2007 |url = http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/stone-sour-made-of-scars-video-posted-online/ |accessdate = July 6, 2009 }}</ref> The fifth and final single from the album, \"Zzyzx Rd.\", started receiving radio airplay in fall 2007; no music video was made for the single.<ref>{{cite news|title=Corey Taylor On Tattoos, 'The Wagon', Divorce And Losing Your Trousers At Festivals |website=Blabbermouth.net |date=September 25, 2007 |url=http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/BLABBERMOUTH.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=81472 |accessdate=July 6, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080518000126/http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=81472 |archivedate=May 18, 2008 }}</ref>\n\nThe band began touring in support of the album before its release, starting with several free shows in the US,<ref>{{cite news |title = Stone Sour To Play Free Concert In Kansas City This Thursday |website = Blabbermouth.net |date = May 15, 2006 |url = http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/stone-sour-to-play-free-concert-in-kansas-city-this-thursday/ |accessdate = July 6, 2009 }}<br>- {{cite news |title = Stone Sour To Play Free Show In Des Moines This Weekend |website = Blabbermouth.net |date = May 16, 2006 |url = http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/stone-sour-to-play-free-show-in-des-moines-this-weekend/ |accessdate = July 6, 2009 }}</ref> followed by appearances at festivals in Europe.<ref name=\"BM5\"/> They then joined [[Korn]] for their 2006 edition of [[Family Values Tour]] across the US, with 33&nbsp;dates across 3&nbsp;months.<ref>{{cite news |title = Korn, Deftones, Stone Sour: 'Family Values' Tour Dates Announced |website = Blabbermouth.net |date = May 16, 2006 |url = http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/korn-deftones-stone-sour-family-values-tour-dates-announced/ |accessdate = July 6, 2009}}</ref> On August 8, 2006, Stone Sour made a special guest appearance on ''[[The Tonight Show with Jay Leno]]'' to promote and perform the second single, \"Through Glass.\"<ref>{{cite news |title = Stone Sour To Perform On 'The Tonight Show With Jay Leno' |website = Blabbermouth.net |date = July 26, 2006 |url = http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/stone-sour-to-perform-on-the-tonight-show-with-jay-leno/ |accessdate = July 6, 2009 }}</ref> They also performed at the Japanese [[Summer Sonic Festival]] midway through the Family Values Tour.<ref>{{cite news |title = Linkin Park Join Metallica As Co-Headliners Of Japan's Summer Sonic Festival |website = Blabbermouth.net |date = March 7, 2006 |url = http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/linkin-park-join-metallica-as-co-headliners-of-japan-s-summer-sonic-festival/ |accessdate = July 6, 2009}}</ref> In November and December 2006, Stone Sour joined [[Disturbed (band)|Disturbed]] for their [[Music as a Weapon Tour]].<ref>{{cite news |last = Harris |first = Chris |title = Disturbed Revive Music As A Weapon Tour With Stone Sour, Flyleaf |publisher = MTV |date = October 5, 2006 |url = http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1542447/20061005/disturbed.jhtml |accessdate = July 6, 2009}}</ref> In January 2007, Stone Sour joined [[Evanescence]] for a Canadian tour,<ref>{{cite news |title = Evanescence And Stone Sour To Team Up For Canadian Tour |website = Blabbermouth.net |date = October 31, 2006 |url = http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/evanescence-and-stone-sour-to-team-up-for-canadian-tour/ |accessdate = July 6, 2009}}</ref> followed by a headlining tour of Europe.<ref>{{cite news |title = Stone Sour: European Tour Dates Announced |website = Blabbermouth.net |date = December 15, 2006 |url = http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/stone-sour-european-tour-dates-announced/ |accessdate = July 6, 2009}}</ref> They then headlined the spring 2007 [[J\u00e4germeister Music Tour]] across the US,<ref>{{cite news |title = Stone Sour, Lacuna Coil, Shadows Fall To Team Up For J\u00e4germeister Music Tour |website = Blabbermouth.net |date = January 10, 2007 |url = http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/stone-sour-lacuna-coil-shadows-fall-to-team-up-for-j-germeister-music-tour/ |accessdate = July 6, 2009 }}</ref> followed by headlining tours in Australia and Japan.<ref>{{cite news |title = Stone Sour: New Corey Taylor Audio Interview Available |website = Blabbermouth.net |date = May 10, 2007 |url = http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=72233 |accessdate = July 6, 2009 |url-status = dead |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20091108234453/http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=72233 |archivedate = November 8, 2009 }}</ref> They then started a tour in Europe playing at festivals and selected headline shows.<ref>{{cite news |title = Stone Sour: Previously Unreleased Song Available For Download |website = Blabbermouth.net |date = June 9, 2007 |url = http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=74297 |accessdate = June 9, 2009 |url-status = dead |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070621233642/http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=74297 |archivedate = June 21, 2007 }}</ref> They finished touring in support of the album with a headlining tour in the US in August and September in 2007.<ref>{{cite news |title = Stone Sour: New U.S. Tour Dates Announced |website = Blabbermouth.net |date = June 1, 2007 |url = http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/stone-sour-new-u-s-tour-dates-announced/ |accessdate = July 6, 2009 }}</ref>\n\n=== Special edition ===\nOn June 26, 2007, Stone Sour released a special edition version of the album with six previously unreleased tracks and a bonus DVD. The DVD included a full concert performance by the band from October 2006 in [[Moscow]] and the music videos for \"30/30-150\", \"Through Glass\",\nand \"Sillyworld\".<ref>{{cite news |title = Stone Sour: More Details Revealed About 'Come What(ever) May' Special-Edition Reissue |website = Blabbermouth.netuth.net |date = May 7, 2007 |url = http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=72150 |accessdate = July 6, 2009 |url-status = dead |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070711171210/http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=72150 |archivedate = July 11, 2007 }}</ref> When talking about the special edition, vocalist Taylor said, \"We really wanted to do something which was really cool,\" saying that it shows the band's different musical elements and them in their live element, which he says \"people really gravitate towards\".<ref>{{cite web |author = ArtisanNewsService |title = Stone Sour ready Special Edition of Come What(ever) May |website = [[YouTube]] |date = June 19, 2007 |url = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=FvN0cNb9xV4 |accessdate = November 23, 2008}}</ref> In addition to this, Stone Sour released a [[live album]] of their concert in Moscow exclusively on [[iTunes]], entitled ''[[Live in Moscow (album)|Live in Moscow]]''.<ref>{{cite news|title=Stone Sour Makes Live 'Album' Available Online |website=Blabbermouth.net |date=August 21, 2007 |url=http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=79199 |accessdate=July 6, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081212020801/http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=79199 |archivedate=December 12, 2008 }}</ref>\n\n== Musical style ==\nIn an interview with MTV in 2006, vocalist Taylor said that ''Come What(ever) May'' was a return to the roots of the band, stating it is \"a lot more from the spirit of what the band started with in 1992\".<ref name=\"MTV1\"/> He noted that some songs were \"very atmospheric\" while others maintained \"the hard rock and the heavy stuff\".<ref name=\"MTV1\"/> Jon Wiederhorn of MTV said that \"for every thrash riff there's a tunefully grungy passage, for every flailing guitar line there's a rock-radio hook.\"<ref name=\"MTV2\"/> When talking about the track \"30/30-150\", he said parts are \"bludgeoning, barbed and heavy\" while others are \"soaring and triumphant\" with the production of Raskulinecz helping to balance the album's heaviness with its radio-accessibility.<ref name=\"MTV2\"/> ''Come What(ever) May''{{'}}s lyrics include themes of \"pain, pleasure, happiness, and grief\".<ref name=\"BM3\"/> The diversity in subjects is evident throughout the album; songs including \"Come What(ever) May\" were politically influenced while the track \"Socio\" is about \"social anxiety attacks\" that Taylor suffered.<ref name=\"BM3\"/> \"Zzyzx Rd\" is a love song written to Taylor's wife for helping him in his struggles against alcoholism and contemplation of suicide.<ref name=\"MTV1\"/><ref name=\"MTV2\">{{cite web |url= http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1534381/20060615/stone_sour.jhtml|title= Corey Taylor Hits Rock Bottom On Way To New Stone Sour LP|author= Jon Wiederhorn|date= June 15, 2006|publisher= MTV|accessdate=December 26, 2009}}</ref> \"I've never written anything like that before, but it was very important for me to tell the world not only how much she saved me, but how much she means to me,\" said Taylor.<ref name=\"BM3\"/> Taylor said there is a common thread with the lyrics throughout the album, saying that they are \"about never forgetting where you came from, who you are and why you do this.\"<ref name=\"MTV2\"/>\n\n== Reception ==\n{{Album ratings\n|rev1 = 411mania.com\n|rev1score = 8.0/10<ref name=\"411mania\"/>\n|rev2 = [[About.com]]\n|rev2score = {{Rating|3.5|5}}<ref name=\"about.com\"/>\n|rev3 = [[Allmusic]]\n|rev3score = {{Rating|3.5|5}}<ref name=\"allmusic-review\">{{cite web |last = Frye |first = Megan |title = Come What(ever) May - Review |website = [[Allmusic]] |url =http://www.allmusic.com/album/come-what-ever-may-mw0000573762 |accessdate = July 22, 2015}}</ref>\n|rev4 = ''[[Blender (magazine)|Blender]]''\n|rev4score = {{Rating|3|5}}<ref>{{cite journal |journal=[[Blender (magazine)|Blender]]|url=http://www.blender.com/guide/new/54022/come-whatever-may.html |title=Blender review}}{{Dead link|date=July 2011}}</ref>\n|rev5 = [[Blabbermouth.net]]\n|rev5score = 7.5/10<ref>{{cite news|work=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|first=Don|last=Kaye|url=http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/showreview.aspx?reviewID=816|title=CD reviews Stone Sour - Come What(ever) May|accessdate=July 12, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060806211951/http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/showreview.aspx?reviewID=816|archivedate=August 6, 2006}}</ref>\n|rev6 = [[IGN]]\n|rev6score = 4.8/10<ref name=\"IGN\"/>\n|rev7 = [[MusicOMH]]\n|rev7Score = {{rating|3|5}}<ref name=\"musicomh\">{{cite web|url=http://www.musicomh.com/albums/stone-sour_0706.htm |title=Stone Sour - Come What(Ever) May |publisher=[[MusicOMH]] |first=Tom |last=Day |date=July 31, 2006 |accessdate=April 27, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100115031612/http://www.musicomh.com/albums/stone-sour_0706.htm |archivedate=January 15, 2010 }}</ref>\n}}\n\n''Come What(ever) May'' was met with generally positive critical reviews. Several reviewers noted how it helped to further establish Stone Sour. Chad Bower of [[About.com]] stated that the band had \"progressed a lot since their debut\", noting that the album was \"very diverse and [allows] the band to show many different sides of their musical personality\".<ref name=\"about.com\">{{Cite web |last = Bower |first = Chad |title = Stone Sour - Come What(ever)May Review |website = [[About.com]] |url = http://heavymetal.about.com/od/cdreviews/fr/stonesour.htm |accessdate = December 29, 2009}}</ref> Megan Frye of [[Allmusic]] opened her review of the album by distinguishing what sets Stone Sour apart musically, writing \"[it's their] ability to create smooth, radio-friendly alternative metal songs while simultaneously not boring the people who have heard way too much from post-grunge groups.\"<ref name=\"allmusic-review\"/> On a similar note, Michael Melchor of ''411mania'' said, \"The band is much better at the craft of songwriting than many of their peers.\"<ref name=\"411mania\">{{Cite web |last = Melchor |first = Michael |title = Stone Sour \u2013 Come What(ever) May Review |website = 411mania |date = August 3, 2006 |url = http://www.411mania.com/music/album_reviews/43555/Stone-Sour-%E2%80%93-Come-What%28ever%29-May-Review.htm |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081123055808/http://www.411mania.com/music/album_reviews/43555/Stone-Sour-%E2%80%93-Come-What(ever)-May-Review.htm |archivedate=23 November 2008 |accessdate = December 29, 2009}}</ref> In contrast, reviewer William Fry of ''[[IGN]]'' criticized the album, writing, \"Stone Sour doesn't do anything inspired, original, or fresh here,\" even calling the album \"completely misdirected, and stonewalled\".<ref name=\"IGN\">{{Cite web |last = Fry |first = William |title = Stone Sour - Come What(ever) May Review |website = [[IGN]] |date = July 31, 2006 |url = http://uk.music.ign.com/articles/722/722021p1.html |accessdate = December 29, 2009 |url-status = dead |archiveurl = https://archive.today/20130103140137/http://uk.music.ign.com/articles/722/722021p1.html |archivedate = January 3, 2013 }}</ref> A particular point of interest for reviewers was how ''Come What(ever) May'' is more melodic than the band's previous album ''Stone Sour''. Melchor of ''411mania'' said the album is \"much more liberal with the balladry and acoustic sounds than its predecessor\"; of the track \"Sillyworld\" he said, \"It sounds like what [[Nickelback]] could be if [[Chad Kroeger]] could write a good melody.\"<ref name=\"411mania\"/> In his review, Chad Bower labeled ''Come What(ever) May'' as a \"very melodic and accessible album\" writing that \"it has a little something for everyone\".<ref name=\"about.com\"/> Similarly, Megan Frye praised the album as an \"unyielding effort from a promising talent\".<ref name=\"allmusic-review\"/>\n\n''Come What(ever) May'' sold over 80,000&nbsp;copies in its first week and entered the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200 chart]] in the United Statesat at #4,<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/stone-sour-come-what-ever-may-passes-half-million-mark-in-u-s/|title= Stone Sour: 'Come What(ever) May' Passes Half-Million Mark In U.S.|date= December 8, 2006|website= Blabbermouth.net|accessdate= December 26, 2009}}</ref> and went on to be certified gold in the UK, Canada and the United States.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/stone-sour-come-what-ever-may-certified-gold-in-canada/|title=Stone Sour: 'Come What(ever) May' Certified Gold In Canada |date=November 21, 2006 |website=Blabbermouth.net |accessdate=December 26, 2009 }}<br>- {{cite web |url=https://www.riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?table=SEARCH |title=RIAA Searchable Database |date=December 11, 2006 |work=Search: \"Stone Sour\" |publisher=[[Recording Industry Association of America]] |accessdate=December 26, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070626050454/http://www.riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?table=SEARCH |archivedate=June 26, 2007 }}</ref> In 2007, the single \"30/30-150\" was nominated for Best Metal Performance at the [[49th Grammy Awards]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=63432 |title=Slayer, Lamb of God, Stone Sour Among Grammy Nominees |date=December 7, 2006 |website=Blabbermouth.net |accessdate=December 26, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070916162618/http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=63432 |archivedate=September 16, 2007 }}</ref>\n\n== Track listing ==\nAll lyrics written by Corey Taylor and composed by Stone Sour (Except \"Wicked Game\").\n{{tracklist\n| total_length = 48:54\n| title1  = [[30/30-150]]\n| length1 = 4:18\n| title2  = Come What(ever) May\n| length2 = 3:39\n| title3  = Hell & Consequences\n| length3 = 3:31\n| title4  = [[Sillyworld]]\n| length4 = 4:08\n| title5  = [[Made of Scars]]\n| length5 = 3:23\n| title6  = Reborn\n| length6 = 3:11\n| title7  = Your God\n| length7 = 4:44\n| title8  = [[Through Glass]]\n| length8 = 4:42\n| title9  = Socio\n| length9 = 3:20\n| title10  = 1st Person\n| length10 = 4:01\n| title11  = Cardiff\n| length11 = 4:42\n| title12  = [[Zzyzx Rd. (song)|Zzyzx Rd.]]\n| length12 = 5:15\n}}\n{{Track listing\n| collapsed        = yes\n| headline         = Japanese bonus tracks\n| total_length     = 52:36\n| title13          = Suffer\n| length13         = 3:42\n\n}}\n{{Track listing\n| collapsed        = yes\n| headline         = Special edition bonus tracks\n| total_length     = 70:49\n| title12          = Zzyzx Rd.\n| note12           = Pop version  \n| length12         = 4:01\n| title13          = Suffer\n| length13     